  "text": "The Apache Kafka GroupCoordinator implementation is distributed across several key Java source files in the group-coordinator module. The architecture consists of three main layers:\n\n## Core Interface and Services\n\n**GroupCoordinator.java** (group-coordinator/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/coordinator/group/GroupCoordinator.java) is the main interface defining the GroupCoordinator API with methods for joinGroup(), syncGroup(), and heartbeat() operations that handle classic consumer groups, modern consumer groups, share groups, and streams groups.\n\n**GroupCoordinatorService.java** and **GroupCoordinatorShard.java** provide the service and shard implementations that delegate to GroupMetadataManager for actual request processing.\n\n## State Machines\n\nThe codebase implements multiple state machines for different group types:\n\n1. **Classic Groups** - ClassicGroupState.java defines an enum with five states:\n   - EMPTY: Group has no members but lingers until offset expiration\n   - PREPARING_REBALANCE: Group is preparing to rebalance\n   - COMPLETING_REBALANCE: Group is awaiting state assignment from leader\n   - STABLE: Group is stable with assigned members\n   - DEAD: Group metadata is being removed\n\n2. **Consumer Groups** - ConsumerGroup.java (in modern/consumer) defines ConsumerGroupState enum with states: EMPTY, ASSIGNING, RECONCILING, STABLE, DEAD\n\n3. **Share Groups** - ShareGroup.java (in modern/share) defines ShareGroupState enum with states: EMPTY, STABLE, DEAD, UNKNOWN\n\n4. **Streams Groups** - StreamsGroup.java (in streams) defines StreamsGroupState enum with states: EMPTY, NOT_READY, ASSIGNING, RECONCILING, STABLE, DEAD\n\n## Request Handlers\n\n**GroupMetadataManager.java** contains the implementation of JoinGroup and SyncGroup request handlers:\n- classicGroupJoin() - Entry point for JoinGroup requests\n- classicGroupJoinToClassicGroup() - Routes new or existing classic groups\n- classicGroupJoinNewMember() - Handles new member joins\n- classicGroupJoinExistingMember() - Handles existing member rejoins\n- syncGroup() - Handles SyncGroup requests from group members\n\nThese methods manage state transitions and coordinate the rebalancing protocol between JoinGroup and SyncGroup phases.\n\n## Heartbeat Expiry Detection\n\n**Heartbeat expiry detection** is implemented in GroupMetadataManager.java through:\n- expireClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat() - Invoked when heartbeat operation expires from timer. Checks if member has satisfied recent heartbeat requirement and removes member from group if heartbeat has expired\n- rescheduleClassicGroupMemberHeartbeat() - Manages scheduling of periodic heartbeat expiration checks using CoordinatorTimer\n- ClassicGroupMember tracks sessionTimeoutMs and rebalanceTimeoutMs for detecting timeouts\n\nThe heartbeat expiry mechanism detects member failures and triggers state transitions:\n- If a member in STABLE state fails heartbeat, group transitions to PREPARING_REBALANCE\n- If all members in PREPARING_REBALANCE have joined by timeout, group transitions to COMPLETING_REBALANCE\n- Members with expired heartbeats are removed from the group\n\n## Member Metadata\n\n**ClassicGroupMember.java** holds member metadata including:\n- memberId and groupInstanceId (for static membership)\n- sessionTimeoutMs and rebalanceTimeoutMs for heartbeat tracking\n- awaitingJoinFuture and awaitingSyncFuture for async coordination\n\n**ModernGroupMember.java** (and subclasses ConsumerGroupMember, ShareGroupMember, StreamsGroupMember) provide modern group member implementations with MemberState tracking (STABLE, UNREVOKED_PARTITIONS, UNRELEASED_PARTITIONS).\n\nThe GroupCoordinator implementation handles all aspects of group membership management, state machine transitions, rebalancing protocol execution, and failure detection through heartbeat expiry mechanisms."
